Package graph

Provides the classes which are necessary for creating and performing operations on graphs. In particular, an interface provides the methods necessary to handle operations involving the addition, removal or access to the elements of the graph. Two complementary interfaces contain the methods for these elements, which are vertices and edges. Moreover, the UndirectedGraph class contains all methods necessary to work with an undirected graph whose number of nodes does not vary.
  • Interface Summary 
    Interface Description
    Edge
    Whether a graph is implemented using an adjacency matrix or a adjacency list, edges are an essential element of a graph as these establish the connection between two nodes.
    Graph
    A graph is a set of vertices (sometimes referred to as nodes) interconnected by edges.
    Vertex
    A vertex is a core element of a graph.
  • Class Summary 
    Class Description
    Link
    The Link class provides an implementation for the methods of the Edge interface.
    Node
    The Node class is an implementation of the Vertex.
    UndirectedGraph
    The UndirectGraph class implements the methods provided by the Graph interface.
  • Exception Summary 
    Exception Description
    EdgeNotFound
    The EdgeNotFound class contains the exception to be thrown when the user attempts to access an edge that does not exist in the graph.
    SameVertex
    The SameVertex class contains the exception to be thrown when the user attempts to access an edge which links a vertex to itself.
    VertexNotFound
    The VertexNotFound class contains the exception to be thrown when the user attempts to access a vertex which does not belong to the graph.
